messages.content: Hey @Liebenfiels, we appreciate your feedback :) Hedera seems to be open to provide a guide for non technical users. You mentioned checksum, staking and accounts, what else would you wish to be explained?

that is good start and then recovery phrases/public keys to combine that when explaining accounts.   Some wallets still offer 12 recovery than 24 and that alone may confuse people if no single standard is followed, as least to explain why some have 12/24, that some are used from hisoric point of view as in Bitcoin. I put a lot of posts on QR-code how to make it, but there is no single standard for now  so can be skipped. Just focus on general walk around infographics for accounts ID + checksum, recovery phrases, staking. That is what most people ask for, the tokens etc later on but that part is easy to follow once people understand basics

messages.content: Thanks @JeromeTHA

It would be really nice if Docs were just a bit more helpful on token services. For example : `autoRenewPeriod` is supposedly a value between 30 and 90 days. That's great and all but do I count it in days? Seconds? What is default value? There's no documentation on this it's just written as a parameter on https://docs.hedera.com/hedera/sdks-and-apis/hedera-api/token-service/tokencreate and htat's all you get

For example this post : https://discord.com/channels/373889138199494658/768621337865486347/1082262553016684564 says the exprity is between 6999999 and 8000001 which kinda doesn't fit the proposed 30-90 days window alleged by docs on expiry of contracts

in addition the tokenservice page could easily have one more column specifying the SC and SDK methods used to set the value. As an example: freezeKey is not defined as `token.freezeKey` but in an array of `IHederaTokenService.TokenKey` which is set to `token.tokenKeys`. Where do I read ab this? How do I know this? what about `tokenType` or `supplyType`

Same goes for `FUNGIBLE_COMMON` or `FINITE` type Constants. We dont have them in SC interfaces? Or are they simply not defined in docs? I have to hope everyone working with SC will remember that the line `token.tokenSupplyType = false;` is not some hotfix I figured on the spot but a thought through decision bcs we have no docs on how to use `TokenSupplyType.FINITE` for better readability in SC instead

Looking at it now it's even more inconsistent as `supplyType` as defined in docs is actually being set in SC as  `token.tokenSupplyType` not `token.supplyType` which is not explained anywhere on this page

You can open an issue in the docs repo on GitHub @VR 
https://github.com/hashgraph/hedera-docs

@Ed Marquez regarding the ethers.js announcement, is there any interest in supporting more hedera specific items there as well? For example, and correct me if I'm wrong, but I'm stuck using the hedera sdk to deploy contracts with autoRenewAccountIds
same with admin key, staked node, etc

That's my understanding as well. EVM tooling (like ethers and web3 js) does not currently provide a way to configure or work with Hedera-specific functionality (autorenew period/account, staking specs, etc.) Atm, the SDK is the only tool to configure those options. 

I'm not aware of plans for the short-term to propose those capabilities on those third party libraries. From previous observations, they're most likely not to welcome the changes to generic tooling to accommodate requirements of a single network.

Let us know if you have any specific thoughts, ideas, or suggestions around this.
It's alright, there are workarounds and we can use both, it's just a pain 🙂
